<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
The last few times I've attended the Greggie I've witnessed the following scenario.  At 11:20pm there is a sudden influx of customers.  Because of the pressure on space many of the newcomers flood into the lower non smoking area, then several of them light up.  At this point someone goes over and informs them they are in a non smoking area.  What follows varies between pantomime, (where the smokers remain in the area but hold their cigarettes through the uprights of the banisters, or exhale generally in the direction of the larger room) via indignant protests, ("I'll stop when I've smoked this one") to insults and threats directed at whoever pointed out the no smoking signs.<BR>The Greggie must be one of the most tolerant social spaces on the planet and let's hope it remains so, but at the moment the combination of a non smoking area and late drinking is creating agro.<BR>The bar staff (bless 'em), never fail to react if the problem is brought to their attention, but this is the busiest time of night and they really have better things to do (like serving beer).<BR>Has anyone a brilliant imaginative solution to this problem?
</FONT>
<HR size="1" color="#5d7790">
